{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dfcff82-f13d-48f2-9aca-850baf27e39a","content":"I can help guide you on analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n**Tools for analyzing .NET crash dumps:**\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze <file.dmp>`** — cross-platform, .NET-focused\n   ```\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze myapp.dmp\n   ```\n   Useful commands inside the REPL:\n   - `clrstack` — managed call stack\n   - `pe` — print last exception\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n   - `sos help` — list all commands\n\n2. **`lldb` (Linux/macOS)** with the SOS plugin:\n   ```\n   dotnet-sos install\n   lldb --core myapp.dmp\n   ```\n\n3. **WinDbg / Visual Studio (Windows)** — open the `.dmp` directly.\n\n**Typical investigation steps:**\n1. Run `pe` (print exception) to see if an unhandled exception caused the crash.\n2. Run `clrstack` / `clrthreads` to inspect thread stacks.\n3. Look for `StackOverflowException`, `AccessViolationException`, or `OutOfMemoryException`.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file? If so, share the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94ed27c4-318b-4f96-b56c-a1f160ed5e19","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description specifically says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":460,"requestId":"608F:2A830E:3113BA:3F990B:69FFE576"},"id":"b8973b2c-befa-4936-914f-8c55b2d43cad","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:55:14.253Z","parentId":"22eac2f1-3779-48d0-a7e8-d0d7fae7c423"}
